ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.
M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported
e.g., Self-Report, Parent Form, Short Form, Revised Version

ElementDescription: The event name for which the data was collected
Were there abnormal neurological exam findings?
Notes: 0= No, abnormal findings; 1= Yes, abnormal findings were consistent with syndromes; 2= Yes. abnormal findings were consistent with age-associated changes or irrelevant to dementing disorders

ElementDescription: Left - Slowing of fine motor movements
Right - Slowing of fine motor movements
Neurological signs considered by examiner to be most likely consistent with cerebrovascular disease
Cortical cognitive deficit (e.g., aphasia, apraxia, neglect)
Focal or other neurological findings consistent with SIVD (subcortical ischemic vascular dementia)
Left - Motor (may include weakness of combinations of face, arm, and left; reflex changes; etc.)
Right - Motor (may include weakness of combinations of face, arm, and left; reflex changes; etc.)
Higher cortical visual problem suggesting posterior cortical atrophy (e.g., prosopagnosia, simultanagnosia, Balints syndrome) or apraxia of gaze.
Findings suggestive of progressive supranuclear palsy (PSP), corticobasal syndrome, or other related disorders.
Eye movement changes consistent with PSP
Left - Cortical sensory deficits consistent with CBS
Left - Alien limb consistent with CBS
Left - Dystonia consistent with CBS, PSP, or related disorder
Right - Cortical sensory deficits consistent with CBS
Right - Alien limb consistent with CBS
Right - Dystonia consistent with CBS, PSP, or related disorder
Findings suggesting ALS (e.g., muscle wasting, fasciculations, upper motor neuron and/or lower motor neuron signs)
Other findings (e.g., cerebellar ataxia, chorea, myoclonus)
